    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 12th with a clear emphasis on aggressive plate appearances against mediocre pitching rotations. **Trea Turner** (72.21) leads the charge today; despite facing a high-caliber arm in Gallen, **Trea Turner** leverages a significant BvP advantage and prime lead-off positioning to anchor our daily output. Following close behind is **Christian Yelich** (71.15), whose platoon edge against the right-handed Littell provides a premium efficiency ceiling. We are also banking on **Colt Keith** (68.60) to exploit a favorable matchup against Alcantara; his combination of high-order placement and an inflated park factor makes him an essential start, particularly given his proximity to the heart of the lineup.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Jerar Encarnacion**, who carried a respectable 55.62 score but was ultimately squeezed out by the depth of our outfield. While **Jerar Encarnacion** benefited from a substantial park factor, the efficiency gap\u2014narrow as it was\u2014favored the versatility of **Kazuma Okamoto** in the UTIL spot. Similarly, **Victor Scott II** (54.41) was considered for his elite speed, but his slot at the bottom of the order and a less-than-ideal matchup against Bello limited his projection enough to keep him on the pine. We are monitoring **Yordan Alvarez** (56.87) closely; his score is suppressed significantly by an elite matchup against Gilbert, and while his talent is undeniable, the math suggests a riskier floor today than we might see in more favorable conditions. \n\nManagers should be aware that while we are deploying **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (56.46) and **Logan O'Hoppe** (56.63) as strong options, both are operating against pitchers with respectable skill sets, capping their upside. With **Hyeseong Kim**, **Zac Veen**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Carson Benge**, and **Luis Pena** remaining on the bench, we retain sufficient depth to pivot if late-breaking lineup changes or adverse weather reports materialize. Maintain focus on the stolen base opportunities afforded by the slower deliveries of our opponents' starters today, as the secondary stats remain our primary target.",
